* Background

** Perturbation theory
[[http://arxiv.org/abs/1203.6448v2][Gauge-invariant variables in general-relativistic perturbations]]

* Personal appreciation of the model

1. During the XX century, models for the four fundamental interactions
   were build, and they have been very successful.
2. On the one hand, the three interactions which explain the phenomena
   in particle physics (electromagnetic, weak and strong) are build on
   the bases of gauge theories, in which the field is a connection. On
   the other hand, gravitation is modelled as a theory for the metric
   field.
3. The gravitational interaction is the only fundamental theory which
   has eluded the quantization process, despite the many attempts
   cite:tHooft:1973us,tHooft:1974bx,Deser:1974cz,Deser:1974cy.
4. It has been known from a long time that the standard theory of
   General Relativity, as proposed by Einstein
   cite:einstein1915feldgleichungen and Hilbert
   cite:hilbert1915grundlagen, was a particular case of a slightly
   general model in which the connection is not necessarily the
   Levi-Civita one, but a general affine connection cite:Cartan1922,Cartan1923,Cartan1924,Cartan1925.
5. The aforementioned generalisation of General Relativity possesses
   two independent fields, the metric and the connection, and they
   need to be varied independently cite:palatini1919deduzione. Such
   approach is commonly known as Palatini formalism, or first order formalism.[fn:7]
6. Palatini's approach to gravity is equivalent to the one by Einstein
   and Hilbert, for the four-dimensional theory of gravity (without
   matter), because in this case the field equations for the
   connection ensure that torsion vanishes and also entails the
   metricity condition, i.e., $\nabla g = 0$.
7. Shortly before the formulation of General Relativity, there were
   proposals for gravitational theories mediated by a connection
   instead of the metric
   cite:Eddington1923math,schrodinger1950space. This idea is very
   appealing to theorists, because the connection is the only
   geometrical object needed for defining the curvature of a spacetime
   (see for example Refs. cite:Cartan1923,schouten2013ricci,Besse).
8. Diverse reinterpretations of General Relativity have been proposed
   in
   Refs. cite:Plebanski:1977zz,kijowski78_new_variat_princ_gener_relat,ferraris81_gener_relat_is_gauge_type_theor,ferraris82_equiv_relat_theor_gravit,Ashtekar:1986yd,Ashtekar:1987gu,Krasnov:2007uu,Krasnov:2007ky,Krasnov:2011pp,Krasnov:2011up,poplawski07_unified_purel_affin_theor_gravit_elect,poplawski07_on_the_nonsy_purel_affin_gravit,Poplawski:2012bw. In
   many of these the idea is not to depend on the metric field to
   interpreting the gravitational interaction. Moreover, a new
   quatization procedure, based in the initial ideas of Gambini and
   Trias cite:Gambini:1980yz,Gambini:1986ew, was developed for
   quantizing the gravitational interactions
   cite:Ashtekar:1986yd,Ashtekar:1987gu,Barbero:1994an,Holst:1995pc,thiemann2007loop.
9. The general action is
   #+BEGIN_EXPORT latex
   \begin{dmath}
     \label{eq:new-action}
     S = \int \bigg[
       B_1 \,
       \ri{\mu\nu}{\mu}{\rho} \bt{\alpha}{\nu}{\beta}
       \bt{\gamma}{\rho}{\delta}
       + B_2 \,
       \ri{\alpha\beta}{\mu}{\rho} \bt{\gamma}{\nu}{\delta}
       \bt{\mu}{\rho}{\nu}
       + B_3 \,
       \ri{\mu\nu}{\mu}{\alpha} \bt{\beta}{\nu}{\ga} A_\delta
       + B_4 \,
       \ri{\alpha\beta}{\sigma}{\rho} \bt{\ga}{\rho}{\delta} A_\sigma
       + B_5 \,
       \ri{\alpha\beta}{\rho}{\rho} \bt{\ga}{\sigma}{\delta} A_\sigma
       + C_1 \,
       \ri{\mu\alpha}{\mu}{\nu} \nabla_\beta \bt{\ga}{\nu}{\delta}
       + C_2 \,
       \ri{\alpha\beta}{\rho}{\rho} \nabla_\sigma
       \bt{\ga}{\sigma}{\delta}
       + D_1 \,
       \bt{\nu}{\mu}{\lambda} \bt{\mu}{\nu}{\alpha} \nabla_\beta
       \bt{\ga}{\lambda}{\delta}
       + D_2 \,
       \bt{\alpha}{\mu}{\beta} \bt{\mu}{\lambda}{\nu} \nabla_\lambda
       \bt{\ga}{\nu}{\delta}
       + D_3 \,
       \bt{\alpha}{\mu}{\nu} \bt{\beta}{\lambda}{\ga} \nabla_\lambda
       \bt{\mu}{\nu}{\delta}
       + D_4 \,
       \bt{\alpha}{\lambda}{\beta} \bt{\ga}{\sigma}{\delta}
       \nabla_\lambda A_\sigma
       + D_5 \,
       \bt{\alpha}{\lambda}{\beta} A_\sigma \nabla_\lambda
       \bt{\ga}{\sigma}{\delta}
       + D_6 \,
       \bt{\alpha}{\lambda}{\beta} A_\ga \nabla_\lambda A_\delta
       + D_7 \,
       \bt{\alpha}{\lambda}{\beta} A_\lambda \nabla_\ga A_\delta
       + E_1 \,
       \nabla_\rho \bt{\alpha}{\rho}{\beta} \nabla_\sigma
       \bt{\ga}{\sigma}{\delta}
       + E_2 \,
       \nabla_\rho \bt{\alpha}{\rho}{\beta} \nabla_\ga A_{\delta}
       + F_1 \,
       \bt{\alpha}{\mu}{\beta} \bt{\ga}{\sigma}{\delta}
       \bt{\mu}{\lambda}{\rho} \bt{\sigma}{\rho}{\lambda}
       + F_2 \,
       \bt{\alpha}{\mu}{\beta} \bt{\ga}{\nu}{\lambda}
       \bt{\delta}{\lambda}{\rho} \bt{\mu}{\rho}{\nu}
       + F_3 \,
       \bt{\nu}{\mu}{\lambda} \bt{\mu}{\nu}{\alpha}
       \bt{\beta}{\lambda}{\ga} A_\delta
       + F_4 \,
       \bt{\alpha}{\mu}{\beta} \bt{\ga}{\nu}{\delta} A_\mu A_\nu
       \bigg] \de{x}^\alpha \we \de{x}^\beta \we \de{x}^\ga \we \de{x}^\delta
   \end{dmath}
   #+END_EXPORT
10. On the other hand, a gauge-like theory for a $GL(4,\R)$ can be
    built up by separating the trace out of the connection. However,
    this is not as interesting, because the decomposition into
    traceless and trace (in the group indices) yields an $SL(4,\R)$
    connection plus an Abelian $\R^*$ connection, the latter is
    similar to the standard Maxwell electrodynamics.
11. In order to find the complete field equations, we shall use a
    similar notation as the introduced by Kijowski[fn:8] in
    Ref. cite:kijowski78_new_variat_princ_gener_relat. 
12. Since the action depends only of the fundamental fields
    (irreducible components of the affine connection), and their first
    derivative, the field equations are given by the Euler--Lagrange
    equation,
    #+BEGIN_EXPORT latex
    \begin{align}
      \label{eq:ELE-conn}
      \partial_\mu
      \left(\frac{\partial\mathscr{L}}{\partial\left(\partial_\mu{\ct{\nu}{\lambda}{\rho}}\right)}\right)
      - \frac{\partial\mathscr{L}}{\partial {\ct{\nu}{\lambda}{\rho}}}
      &=   0,
      \\
      \label{eq:ELE-B}
      \partial_\mu
      \left(\frac{\partial\mathscr{L}}{\partial\left(\partial_\mu{\bt{\nu}{\lambda}{\rho}}\right)}\right)
      - \frac{\partial\mathscr{L}}{\partial {\bt{\nu}{\lambda}{\rho}}}
      &=   0,
      \\
      \label{eq:ELE-A}
      \partial_\mu
      \left(\frac{\partial\mathscr{L}}{\partial\left(\partial_\mu{ A_{\nu}}\right)}\right)
      - \frac{\partial\mathscr{L}}{\partial { A_{\nu}}}
      &=   0.
    \end{equation}
    #+END_EXPORT
13. *Field equations for the symmetric connection.*
    - First we define the canonical momenta for the connection
      component,
      #+BEGIN_EXPORT latex
      \begin{equation}
        \PG{\mu\nu}{\lambda}{\rho} = \frac{ \partial \Lag }{
          \partial \, \partial_\mu \ct{\nu}{\lambda}{\rho} } \equiv \frac{ \partial \Lag }{
          \partial \,  \ct{\mu\nu}{\lambda}{\rho} }.
      \end{equation}
      #+END_EXPORT
    - Then they are calculated using the chain rule,
      #+BEGIN_EXPORT latex
      \begin{equation}
        \label{eq:def-PG}
        \PG{\mu\nu}{\lambda}{\rho} = \frac{\partial \Lag}{\partial
          \ri{\alpha\beta}{\gamma}{\delta}}
        \frac{\ri{\alpha\beta}{\ga}{\delta}}{\partial
          \ct{\mu\nu}{\lambda}{\rho}} \equiv \PG*[z]{\mu\nu}{\lambda}{\rho}
        \frac{\ri{\alpha\beta}{\ga}{\delta}}{\partial
          \ct{\mu\nu}{\lambda}{\rho}}.
      \end{equation}
      #+END_EXPORT
    - The last term in eq. eqref:eq:def-PG can be calculated
      explicitly from the definition of the curvature tensor,
      #+BEGIN_EXPORT latex
      \begin{equation}
        \label{eq:der-R-wrt-pG}
        \frac{\ri{\alpha\beta}{\ga}{\delta}}{\partial
          \ct{\mu\nu}{\lambda}{\rho}} = 4 \, \delta ^\ga_\lambda
        \delta^\mu_{[\alpha} \delta^{(\nu}_{\beta]} \delta^{\rho)}_\delta,
      \end{equation}
      #+END_EXPORT
      from which it follows that
      #+BEGIN_EXPORT latex
      \begin{equation}
        \label{eq:PG-from-z}
        \PG{\mu\nu}{\lambda}{\rho} = 2 \PG*[z]{[\mu\nu]}{\lambda}{\rho} + 2 \PG*[z]{[\mu\rho]}{\lambda}{\nu}.
      \end{equation}
      #+END_EXPORT
    - The last equation implies that the canonical momenta satisfy the
      Jacobi--Bianchi identity,
      #+BEGIN_EXPORT latex
      \begin{equation}
        \PG{[\mu\nu}{\lambda}{\rho]} = 0.
      \end{equation}
      #+END_EXPORT
    - On the other hand, the second term in the Euler--Lagrange
      equations for $\Gamma$ yields
      #+BEGIN_EXPORT latex
      \begin{equation}
        \frac{\partial \Lag}{\partial \ct{\nu}{\lambda}{\rho}} =
        \frac{\partial \Lag}{\partial \ri{\alpha\beta}{\ga}{\delta}}
        \frac{\partial \ri{\alpha\beta}{\ga}{\delta}}{\partial \ct{\nu}{\lambda}{\rho}}.
      \end{equation}
      #+END_EXPORT
    - Once again the last term can be calculated from the definition
      of curvature
      #+BEGIN_EXPORT latex
      \begin{equation}
        \frac{\partial \ri{\alpha\beta}{\ga}{\delta}}{\partial
          \ct{\nu}{\lambda}{\rho}} = 4 \Big[  \delta^\ga_\lambda
          \delta^{(\nu}_{[\alpha} \ct{\beta]}{\rho)}{\delta} + \delta^\rho_\delta
          \delta^{(\nu}_{[\beta} \ct{\alpha]}{\ga)}{\lambda} \Big],
      \end{equation}
      #+END_EXPORT
      and then,
      #+BEGIN_EXPORT latex
      \begin{align}
        \frac{ \partial \Lag }{ \partial \ct{\nu}{\lambda}{\rho} }
        & =
        2 \, \Big[ \PG*[z]{[\nu\beta]}{\lambda}{\delta}
          \ct{\beta}{\rho}{\delta} + \PG*[z]{[\rho\beta]}{\lambda}{\delta}
          \ct{\beta}{\nu}{\delta} + \PG*[z]{[\beta\nu]}{\ga}{\rho}
          \ct{\beta}{\ga}{\lambda} + \PG*[z]{[\beta\rho]}{\ga}{\nu}
          \ct{\beta}{\ga}{\lambda} \Big] \notag
        \\
        & =
        \frac{1}{2} \PG{\nu\beta}{\lambda}{\delta} \ct{\beta}{\rho}{\delta}
        + \frac{1}{2} \PG{\rho\beta}{\lambda}{\delta}
        \ct{\beta}{\nu}{\delta}
        + \PG{\beta\nu}{\ga}{\rho} \ct{\beta}{\ga}{\lambda} \notag
        \\
        & =
        - \PG{\mu\nu}{\lambda}{\delta} \ct{\mu}{\rho}{\delta}
        - \PG{\mu\rho}{\lambda}{\delta}
        \ct{\mu}{\nu}{\delta}
        + \PG{\mu\nu}{\ga}{\rho} \ct{\mu}{\ga}{\lambda}
        .
        \label{eq:der-L-wrt-G}
      \end{align}
      #+END_EXPORT
    - Therefore, the field equations for the symmetric part of the
      connection are
      #+BEGIN_EXPORT latex
      \begin{equation}
        \label{eq:EOM-G}
        \nabla_\mu \PG{\mu\nu}{\lambda}{\rho} = \frac{\partial^*
          \Lag}{\partial \ct{\nu}{\lambda}{\rho} }.
      \end{equation}
      #+END_EXPORT
      In this last equation, we have used the fact that the canonical
      momenta are densities, thus there are two term (which seems to
      be missing above) that cancel themselves.[fn:9] The the asterisk
      on the RHS of Eq. eqref:eq:EOM-G denotes the partial derivative
      with respect to the connection that is not contained in the
      curvature tensor.
    - Notice that there are seven term in which the symmetric part of
      the connection enters through the curvature tensor, while it
      enters through the covariant derivative of the tensors
      $\bt{}{}{}$ and $A$ in eleven terms. Noteworthily, there are
      only two terms in which the symmetric part of the connection
      enters in both ways, these are the terms in the action with
      coupling constants $C_1$ and $C_2$.
    - Additionally, the terms in the action with couplings $C_1$ and
      $C_2$ are the only which are linear in either $\bt{}{}{}$ and
      $A$ fields. Therefore, there are the terms which could possibly
      contribute to the field equations in the sector of vanishing
      torsion, i.e., $\bt{}{}{} \to 0$ and $A \to 0$.
    - *Calculation of the $\PG{\mu\nu}{\lambda}{\rho}$.*
      We start calculating the $\PG*[z]{\mu\nu}{\lambda}{\rho}$ and
      then use the Eq. eqref:eq:PG-from-z, to obtain[fn:10]
      #+BEGIN_EXPORT latex
      \begingroup
      \allowdisplaybreaks
      \begin{align}
        & B_1: &
        \PG{\mu\nu}{\lambda}{\rho} &= \Big[ 2
          \delta^{[\mu}_\lambda \bt{\alpha}{\nu]}{\beta}
          \bt{\ga}{\rho}{\delta} + 2 \delta^{[\mu}_\lambda
            \bt{\alpha}{\rho]}{\beta} \bt{\ga}{\nu}{\delta} \Big]
        \de{x}^{\alpha\beta\ga\delta}
        \\
        & B_2: &
        \PG{\mu\nu}{\lambda}{\rho} &=
        2 \bt{\ga}{\sigma}{\delta} \bt{\sigma}{(\rho}{\lambda} \de{x}^{\nu)\mu\ga\delta}
        \\
        & B_3: &
        \PG{\mu\nu}{\lambda}{\rho} &= 
        2 \delta^{[\mu}_\lambda \bt{\beta}{\nu]}{\ga} A_\delta
        \de{x}^{\rho\beta\ga\delta} + 2 \delta^{[\mu}_\lambda \bt{\beta}{\rho]}{\ga} A_\delta
        \de{x}^{\nu\beta\ga\delta}
        \\
        & B_4: &
        \PG{\mu\nu}{\lambda}{\rho} &=
        -2 \bt{\ga}{(\rho}{\delta} A_\lambda \de{x}^{\nu)\mu\ga\delta}
        \\
        & B_5: &
        \PG{\mu\nu}{\lambda}{\rho} &=
        -2 \bt{\ga}{\sigma}{\delta} A_\sigma \delta^{(\rho}_\lambda
        \de{x}^{\nu)\mu\ga\delta}
        \\
        & C_1: &
        \PG{\mu\nu}{\lambda}{\rho} &=
        2 \nabla_\beta \bt{\ga}{\rho}{\delta} \delta^{[\mu}_\lambda
          \de{x}^{\nu]\beta\ga\delta} + 2 \nabla_\beta \bt{\ga}{\nu}{\delta}
        \delta^{[\mu}_\lambda \de{x}^{\rho]\beta\ga\delta}
        \\
        & C_2: &
        \PG{\mu\nu}{\lambda}{\rho} &=
        - 2 \nabla_\sigma \bt{\ga}{\sigma}{\delta} \delta^{(\rho}_\lambda \de{x}^{\nu)\mu\ga\delta}
      \end{align}
      \endgroup
      #+END_EXPORT
    - *Calculation of $\frac{\partial^\star \Lag}{\partial \ct{\nu}{\lambda}{\rho} }$.*
      - In Eq. eqref:eq:new-action, the connection appears explicitly
        (non in the curvature tensor) in the covariant
        derivative. However, the covariant derivative contains different
        terms depending on the field it is acting on.
      - The two different terms in which the connection appears are
        #+BEGIN_EXPORT latex
        \begin{equation}
          \label{eq:nablaB}
          \nabla_\alpha \bt{\beta}{\ga}{\delta} = \partial_\alpha
          \bt{\beta}{\ga}{\delta} + \ct{\alpha}{\lambda}{\beta}
          \bt{\lambda}{\ga}{\delta} + \ct{\alpha}{\lambda}{\delta}
          \bt{\beta}{\ga}{\lambda} - \ct{\alpha}{\ga}{\lambda} \bt{\beta}{\lambda}{\delta}
        \end{equation}
        #+END_EXPORT
        and
        #+BEGIN_EXPORT latex
        \begin{equation}
          \label{eq:nablaA}
          \nabla_\alpha A_\beta = \partial_\alpha A_\beta -
          \ct{\alpha}{\lambda}{\beta} A_\lambda.
        \end{equation}
        #+END_EXPORT
      - Now their partial derivatives with respect to the connection are
        #+BEGIN_EXPORT latex
        \begin{equation}
          \label{eq:der-nablaB-G}
          \frac{\partial \nabla_\alpha \bt{\beta}{\ga}{\delta} }{ \partial
            \ct{\nu}{\lambda}{\rho} } = 2 \delta^{(\nu}_{\alpha}
          \delta^{\rho)}_{\beta} \bt{\lambda}{\ga}{\delta} + 2 \delta^{(\nu}_{\alpha}
          \delta^{\rho)}_{\delta} \bt{\beta}{\ga}{\lambda} - 2
          \delta^c_\lambda \delta^{(\nu}_\alpha \bt{\beta}{\rho)}{\delta}
        \end{equation}
        #+END_EXPORT
        and
        #+BEGIN_EXPORT latex
        \begin{equation}
          \label{eq:der-nablaA-G}
          \frac{ \nabla_\alpha A_\beta}{\partial \ct{\nu}{\lambda}{\rho}} = -
          2 \delta^{(\nu}_\alpha \delta^{\rho)}_\beta A_\lambda.
        \end{equation}
        #+END_EXPORT
      - The terms coming from these derivatives are
        #+BEGIN_EXPORT latex
        \begingroup
        \allowdisplaybreaks
        \begin{align}
          & C_1: &
          \frac{\partial \Lag}{\partial \ct{\nu}{\lambda}{\rho} } &=
          -2 \ri{\mu\lambda}{\mu}{\alpha} \delta^{(\nu}_\beta
          \bt{\ga}{\rho)}{\delta} \de{x}^{\alpha\beta\ga\delta} \notag
          \\
          & & &=
          2 \ri{\mu\lambda}{\mu}{\alpha} 
          \bt{\ga}{(\rho}{\delta} \de{x}^{\nu)\alpha\ga\delta}
          \\
          & C_2: &
          \frac{\partial \Lag}{\partial \ct{\nu}{\lambda}{\rho} } &=
          2 \ri{\alpha\beta}{\sigma}{\sigma} \Big[ 
            \delta^{(\rho}_\ga \bt{\lambda}{\nu)}{\delta} +
            \delta^{(\rho}_\delta \bt{\ga}{\nu)}{\lambda} -
            \delta^{(\nu}_\lambda \bt{\ga}{\rho)}{\delta}
            \Big]
          \de{x}^{\alpha\beta\ga\delta}
          \\
          & & &=
          2 \ri{\alpha\beta}{\sigma}{\sigma} \Big[
            2 \bt{\lambda}{(\nu}{\delta} \de{x}^{\rho)\alpha\beta\delta}
            - \delta^{(\nu}_\lambda \bt{\ga}{\rho)}{\delta}
            \de{x}^{\alpha\beta\ga\delta}
            \Big]
          \\
          & D_1: &
          \frac{\partial \Lag}{\partial \ct{\nu}{\lambda}{\rho} } &=
          - 2 \bt{\tau}{\sigma}{\lambda} \bt{\sigma}{\tau}{\alpha}
          \delta^{(\nu}_\beta \bt{\ga}{\rho)}{\delta}
          \de{x}^{\alpha\beta\ga\delta}
          \\
          & & &=
          2 \bt{\tau}{\sigma}{\lambda} \bt{\sigma}{\tau}{\alpha}
          \bt{\ga}{(\rho}{\delta}
          \de{x}^{\nu)\alpha\ga\delta}
          \\
          & D_2: &
          \frac{\partial \Lag}{\partial \ct{\nu}{\lambda}{\rho} } &=
          2 \bt{\alpha}{\sigma}{\beta} \bt{\sigma}{(\nu}{\tau} \Big[
            \delta^{\rho)}_\ga \bt{\lambda}{\tau}{\delta} +
            \delta^{\rho)}_\delta \bt{\ga}{\tau}{\lambda} -
            \delta^{\tau}_\lambda \bt{\ga}{|\rho)}{\delta}
            \Big]
          \de{x}^{\alpha\beta\ga\delta}
          \\
          & & &=
          2 \bt{\alpha}{\sigma}{\beta} \bt{\sigma}{(\nu}{\tau} \Big[
            2 \bt{\lambda}{\tau}{\delta}
            \de{x}^{|\rho)\alpha\beta\delta} -
            \delta^{\tau}_\lambda \bt{\ga}{|\rho)}{\delta}
            \de{x}^{\alpha\beta\ga\delta}
            \Big]
          \\
          & D_3: &
          \frac{\partial \Lag}{\partial \ct{\nu}{\lambda}{\rho} } &=
          2 \bt{\alpha}{\sigma}{\tau} \bt{\beta}{(\nu}{\ga} \Big[
            \delta^{\rho)}_\sigma \bt{\lambda}{\tau}{\delta}
            + \delta^{\rho)}_\delta \bt{\sigma}{\tau}{\lambda}
            - \delta^\tau_\lambda \bt{\sigma}{|\rho)}{\delta}
            \Big]
          \de{x}^{\alpha\beta\ga\delta}
          \\
          & D_4: &
          \frac{\partial \Lag}{\partial \ct{\nu}{\lambda}{\rho} } &=
          - 2 \bt{\alpha}{\nu}{\beta} \bt{\ga}{\rho}{\delta} A_\lambda
          \de{x}^{\alpha\beta\ga\delta}
          \\
          & D_5: &
          \frac{\partial \Lag}{\partial \ct{\nu}{\lambda}{\rho} } &=
          2 \bt{\alpha}{(\nu}{\beta} A_\sigma \Big[
            2 \bt{\lambda}{\sigma}{\delta} \de{x}^{|\rho)\alpha\beta\delta}
            - \delta^\sigma_\lambda \bt{\ga}{|\rho)}{\delta}
            \de{x}^{\alpha\beta\ga\delta}
            \Big]
          \\
          & D_6: &
          \frac{\partial \Lag}{\partial \ct{\nu}{\lambda}{\rho} } &=
          2 \bt{\alpha}{(\nu}{\beta} A_\ga A_\lambda
          \de{x}^{\rho)\alpha\beta\ga}
          \\
          & D_7: &
          \frac{\partial \Lag}{\partial \ct{\nu}{\lambda}{\rho} } &=
          0
          \\
          & E_1: &
          \frac{\partial \Lag}{\partial \ct{\nu}{\lambda}{\rho} } &=
          4 \nabla_\sigma \bt{\alpha}{\sigma}{\beta} \Big[
            2 \bt{\lambda}{(\rho}{\delta} \de{x}^{\nu)\alpha\beta\delta}
            - \delta^{(\nu}_\lambda \bt{\ga}{\rho)}{\delta}
            \de{x}^{\alpha\beta\ga\delta}
            \Big]
          \\
          & E_2: &
          \frac{\partial \Lag}{\partial \ct{\nu}{\lambda}{\rho} } &=
          2 F_{\alpha\beta} \Big[
            2 \bt{\lambda}{(\rho}{\delta} \de{x}^{\nu)\alpha\beta\delta}
            - \delta^{(\nu}_\lambda \bt{\ga}{\rho)}{\delta}
            \de{x}^{\alpha\beta\ga\delta}
            \Big]
        \end{align}
        \endgroup
        #+END_EXPORT
    - Notice that in the last set of contributions, the one coming
      from the term accompanied by the coupling $D_7$ yields
      zero. This is because the antisymmetrization of $\nabla A$ is
      nothing but the field strength of the potential $A$ (or the
      curvature of an Abelian 1-form). The strength does not depend on
      the connection.
    - 
14. *Field equations for the $B$ field.*
    Using the relations
    #+BEGIN_EXPORT latex
    \begin{equation}
      \frac{ \partial \nabla_\alpha \bt{\beta}{\ga}{\delta} }{ \partial
        \partial_\mu \bt{\nu}{\lambda}{\rho} }
      =
      2 \delta^\mu_a \delta^\ga_\lambda \delta^{[\nu}_\beta \delta^{\rho]}_\delta
    \end{equation}
    #+END_EXPORT
    and
    #+BEGIN_EXPORT latex
    \begin{equation}
      \frac{ \partial \nabla_\alpha \bt{\beta}{\ga}{\delta} }{ \partial
         \bt{\nu}{\lambda}{\rho} }
      =
      - 2 \ct{\alpha}{[\nu}{\beta} \delta^{\rho]}_\delta
      \delta^\ga_\lambda
      - 2 \ct{\alpha}{[\rho}{\delta} \delta^{\nu]}_\beta
      \delta^\ga_\lambda
      + 2 \ct{\alpha}{\ga}{\lambda} \delta^{[\nu}_\beta \delta^{\rho]}_\delta
    \end{equation}
    #+END_EXPORT
    it is straightforward to show that the equations of motion for the
    $\bt{}{}{}$ field are[fn:11]
    #+BEGIN_EXPORT latex
    h
    #+END_EXPORT
15. *Field equations for the $A$ field.*
    Here are presented the /complete/ Euler--Lagrage equations for
    the $A$ field, considering the piece-wise Lagrangian density.
    #+BEGIN_EXPORT latex
    \begingroup
    \allowdisplaybreaks
    \begin{align}
      & B_3: &
      \ri{\sigma\tau}{\sigma}{\alpha} \bt{\beta}{\tau}{\ga}
      \de{x}^{\alpha\beta\ga\nu}
      &= 0
      \\
      & B_4: &
      \ri{\alpha\beta}{\nu}{\sigma} \bt{\ga}{\sigma}{\delta}
      \de{x}^{\alpha\beta\ga\delta}
      &= 0
      \\
      & B_5: &
      \ri{\alpha\beta}{\sigma}{\sigma} \bt{\ga}{\nu}{\delta}
      \de{x}^{\alpha\beta\ga\delta}
      &= 0
      \\
      & D_4 &
      \nabla_\mu \Big[
        \bt{\alpha}{\mu}{\beta} \bt{\ga}{\nu}{\delta}
        \de{x}^{\alpha\beta\ga\delta} \Big]
      &= 0
      \\
      & D_5: &
      \bt{\alpha}{\sigma}{\beta} \nabla_\sigma \bt{\ga}{\nu}{\delta}
      \de{x}^{\alpha\beta\ga\delta}
      &= 0
      \\
      & D_6: &
      \nabla_\mu \Big[
        \bt{\alpha}{\mu}{\beta} A_\ga \de{x}^{\alpha\beta\ga\nu}
        \Big]
      + \bt{\alpha}{\mu}{\beta} \nabla_\mu A_\ga
      \de{x}^{\alpha\beta\ga\nu}
      &= 0
      \\
      & D_7: &
      \nabla_\mu \Big[
        \bt{\alpha}{\sigma}{\beta} A_\sigma \de{x}^{\alpha\beta\mu\nu}
        \Big]
      + \bt{\alpha}{\nu}{\beta} F_{\ga\delta}
      \de{x}^{\alpha\beta\ga\delta}
      &= 0
      \\
      & E_2: &
      \nabla_\mu \Big[ \nabla_\sigma \bt{\alpha}{\sigma}{\beta}
        \de{x}^{\alpha\beta\mu\nu} \Big]
      &= 0
      \\
      & F_3: &
      \bt{\sigma}{\tau}{\lambda} \bt{\tau}{\sigma}{\alpha}
      \bt{\beta}{\lambda}{\ga} \de{x}^{\alpha\beta\ga\nu}
      &= 0
      \\
      & F_4: &
      2 \bt{\alpha}{\sigma}{\beta} \bt{\ga}{\nu}{\delta} A_\sigma
      \de{x}^{\alpha\beta\ga\delta}
      &= 0
    \end{align}
    \endgroup
    #+END_EXPORT
    


