* Footnotes

[fn:11] Following a procedure similar to the one for the symmetric
$\ct{}{}{}$'s.

[fn:10] We introduce the notation $\de{x}^{\alpha\beta\ga\delta}
\equiv \de{x}^\alpha \we \de{x}^\beta \we \de{x}^\ga \we \de{x}^\delta$. 

[fn:9] The covariant derivative of this tensor density is given by the
expression,
#+BEGIN_EXPORT latex
\begin{dmath*}
\nabla_\sigma \PG{\mu\nu}{\lambda}{\rho} = \partial_\sigma \PG{\mu\nu}{\lambda}{\rho} + \ct{\sigma}{\mu}{\tau} \PG{\tau\nu}{\lambda}{\rho} + 
\ct{\sigma}{\nu}{\tau} \PG{\mu\tau}{\lambda}{\rho} - \ct{\sigma}{\tau}{\lambda} \PG{\mu\nu}{\tau}{\rho} +
\ct{\sigma}{\rho}{\tau} \PG{\mu\nu}{\lambda}{\tau} - \ct{\sigma}{\tau}{\tau} \PG{\mu\nu}{\lambda}{\rho},
\end{dmath*}
#+END_EXPORT
then, when one contract the $\sigma$ and $\mu$ indices, the second and
sixth terms in the RHS cancel each other.

[fn:8] Our notation is inspired by that of the cited work, but it
might differs in both symbols and signs. We advise to be careful if
you would like to compare the results.

[fn:7] The name first order formalism is because for the standard
theory of gravity the field equations are second order, while they
turn into first order equations when one varies the metric and the
connection independently. 

[fn:6] 

[fn:5] Notice that in four dimensions and affine connection has
sixty-four components. Therefore, there are one hundred and ninety two
differential equations to solve for the three generators of spherical
symmetry.

[fn:4] The inhomogeneous algebra of \(ISO(n)\) can be obtained from
the ones of \(SO(n+1)\) or \(SO(n,1)\) through the Inönü--Wigner
contraction cite:Gilmore. 

[fn:3] The field equations can be consistently truncated under the
requirement of vanishing torsion. It is worth noticing that this
condition does not yield the Riemannian theory, since we are not yet
asking for a metricity condition.

[fn:2] power-counting renormalizability does not guarantee
renormalizability.

[fn:1] An example of four-dimensional topological term is the Euler density.
